Topic: Linear algebra

Content: Linear algebra is the branch of mathematics concerning linear equations such as
{\displaystyle a_{1}x_{1}+\cdots +a_{n}x_{n}=b,}
{\displaystyle (x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})\mapsto a_{1}x_{1}+\cdots +a_{n}x_{n},}
and their representations in vector spaces and through matrices.
Linear algebra is central to almost all areas of mathematics. For instance, linear algebra is fundamental in modern presentations of geometry, including for defining basic objects such as lines, planes and rotations. Also, functional analysis, a branch of mathematical analysis, may be viewed as the application of linear algebra

Topic: Linear algebra — Linear maps

Content: Linear maps are mappings between vector spaces that preserve the vector-space structure. Given two vector spaces V and W over a field F, a linear map (also called, in some contexts, linear transformation or linear mapping) is a map
{\displaystyle T:V\to W}
that is compatible with addition and scalar multiplication, that is
{\displaystyle T(\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v} )=T(\mathbf {u} )+T(\mathbf {v} ),\quad T(a\mathbf {v} )=aT(\mathbf {v} )}
for any vectors u,v in V and scalar a in F.
An equivalent condition is that
{\displaystyle T(a\mathbf {u} +b\mathbf {v} )=aT(\mathbf {u} )+bT(\mathbf {v} )}
